computeAuctionIndex(address,uint256,uint.details: compute largest auctionIndex with clearing time smaller than desired time. Use case: user provides a time and this function will find the largest auctionIndex that had a cleared auction before that time. It is used to get historical price oracle values

params.initialUpperBound: initial upper bound when this recursive fn is called for the first time
params.lowerBound: lowerBound of result. Recommended that it is > 0, because 0th price is set by whoever adds token pair
params.token: address of ERC-20 token in question
address of ERC-20 token in question

getPrice(address).return: The numerator of the price of the tokenThe denominator of the price of the token

getPriceCustom(address,uint256,bool,uint.details: More fine-grained price oracle for token `token.address()`

params.maximumTimePeriod: maximum time period between clearing time of last auction and `time`
params.requireWhitelisted: Require the token be whitelisted on the DutchX? (Unwhitelisted addresses might not conform to the ERC-20 standard and/or might be malicious)
params.time: 0 for current price, a Unix timestamp for a price at any point in time
params.token: address of ERC-20 token in question

getPriceCustom(address,uint256,bool,uint.return: The numerator of the price of the tokenThe denominator of the price of the token

getPricesAndMedian(address,uint256,uint2.details: search starts at auctionIndex - 1. The reason for this is we expect the most common use case to be the latest auction index and for that the clearingTime is not available yet. So we need to start at the one before

params.token: address of ERC-20 token in question

params.token: address of ERC-20 token in question
